<body>
<div type="description" n="monument">
<head>Description of Monument</head>
<p><rs type="material" key="marmor">White marble</rs> <rs type="objectType">statue base</rs> with upper moulding, which is broken (<measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">0.39</measure>, face -  <measure dim="width" type="length" precision="circa">0.50</measure> with moulding, x <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">0.63</measure>   × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="depth">0.55</measure>).

</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="text">
<head>Description of Text</head>
<p><rs type="execution" key="scalpro">Inscribed</rs> on moulding (ll. 1-2) and on face.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="letters">
<head>Letters</head>
<p>Not particularly well cut; <measure dim="none">0.04- 0.045</measure>.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="date">
<head>Date</head>
<p>
<date notBefore="0151" notAfter="0200">Second half of second century A.D.</date>
(<rs type="criteria">lettering</rs>, <rs type="criteria">monument group</rs>, <rs type="criteria">prosopography</rs>).</p>
</div>
<div type="edition" lang="grc">
<head lang="en">Edition</head>
<ab><lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="1" unit="character"/>  <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Οὐλπία"><unclear reason="damage">Οὐλπ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ία</supplied></name>  <name reg="Ἀπολλώνιος"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀπο</supplied><lb n="2" type="worddiv"/><supplied reason="lost">λ</supplied>λωνίου</name> <w><unclear reason="damage">πρε</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ιμο</supplied><lb n="3" type="worddiv"/>      πειλαρίου</w>  <w lemma="καί">καὶ</w><lb n="4"/> <w lemma="ἀπό">ἀπὸ</w> <w>στρατο<lb n="5" type="worddiv"/>πεδαρχίας</w><lb n="6"/> <w>θυγατὴρ</w> <name reg="Ἀπολλωνία">Ἀπολ<lb n="7" type="worddiv"/>      λωνία</name></persName> <w lemma="ὁ">τῇ</w> <w>Πα<lb n="8" type="worddiv"/>      <g type="scroll"/>  τρίδι</w>  <g type="leaf"/></ab>
</div>


<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>Ulpia Apollonia, daughter of Apollonius, <term lang="la">primipilarius</term>, and former camp prefect, to her homeland.</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>One of the series of dedications from the East Court of the Hadrianic Baths: <xref type="iAph">1184</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1186</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1187</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1188</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1189</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1190</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1191</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1192</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1193</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1194</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1195</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1196</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1197</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1198</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1200</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1201</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1202</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1203</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1204</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1205</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1206</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1207</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1208</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1209</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1210</xref> ; all are by women, and apparently bore caryatids (see <xref type="iAph">1198</xref>).</p><p><xref type="iAph">1200</xref> (=84.55) is the same text, but with a different layout.</p>
</div>
